WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Hello again, everybody. My name is Alex Chisholm. I'm on the Posit Cloud team here at Posit.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Thank you for joining us for this third episode in our live demo series.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Today we're going to turn to a new feature that we put into the product in the middle or late August called Project Templates.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.000
And what Project Templates enable you to do is speed up your workflows

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:33.000
when you have a core set of items that you want to put in the same project over and over and over again.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
We make it easy to surface those, and we're going to take a look at that today.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:45.000
So you probably are aware, for those of you who have joined before, once you're on Posit Cloud, it's pretty easy to start a new project.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Typically, you're going in and you're just clicking New Project and you're creating either a Blank RStudio project or a Jupyter Notebook project.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.000
Maybe you're pulling something in from GitHub, from a GitHub repo.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:05.000
And what we've added to this flow is this ability to create a new project from a template.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:11.000
There are several circumstances, right, where this functionality might be useful to you,

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:17.000
because every time on Posit Cloud you're creating a new project, it's really a blank canvas, a blank slate.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
It's up to you to decide which packages to install, which data connections to make.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:30.000
And what you can do with a template, if you find yourself with a recurring workflow, maybe you always use the same set of packages.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Maybe you need to bring in data sets or flat files that don't change very often.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
You want them to be used across all of your projects.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Maybe you know that a certain type of project is going to have a lot more compute requirements

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:51.000
and you want to be able to set your memory or your CPU at a higher level.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Or maybe you just want to get into some of those fine details that you might find in something like project settings in the RStudio IDE

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.000
and you want this to come up every single time that you're opening this new project.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
So this is what project templates enable you to do.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And there are two ways for you to start interacting with templates on Posit Cloud today.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:20.000
The first one is you have the ability to select from, I think, six predefined, pre-configured templates

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:28.000
that have been put together by thought leaders and experts around Posit and that are now on Posit Cloud.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.000
So that's the first way. It helps you get started more quickly.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
You can see some examples, see some sample code, data sets,

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:45.000
and have all the libraries and packages you need to work on those workflows without setting up stuff for yourself.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Secondly, you have the ability to design your own template.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.000
And this is the one that's going to become more powerful the more you use it, I believe.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.000
So here you're going to be able to create a new project,

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:01.000
do everything you need to do based upon those four items we mentioned on the previous slide.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:07.000
And then you're going to be able to call this template again and again and again when you're doing subsequent work.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:12.000
And we're also going to see the ability to make what you do in this template to default

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:17.000
anytime you start a new project from within that space.

